huntBios.GENERAL_INFORMATION: This unit is managed for a total wintering population of 700 elk. Hunts on this unit are typically very low success. Large amounts of snow will typically increase hunter success.
huntBios.WEATHER_CONS: Hunt takes place in December, expect cold temperatures and snow.
huntBios.MANAGEMENT_OBJ: 25.9~~~~~~~~~~~~For more detailed information on population and objective data please see the Big Game Annual Report Page.
huntBios.BIOLOGIST_NOTES:
Migration Patterns: There are more elk on the Anthro unit in the winter than there are in the summer and early fall. Many elk migrate from surrounding units to winter on the Anthro. Some elk come all the way from the Strawberry Reservoir area. The migration is typically elk coming from the West to winter further East. This migration can start as early as October, after the rut. There is, however, a fair amount of resident elk scattered across the entire unit, even on the desert parts on the East half of the unit.

Scouting Tips: The unit is large with elk scattered across most of it. Spend some time before your hunt to learn the roads and access points. There are many springs and guzzlers on the unit and these are typically the best places to find elk during the summer and fall. This is a general season hunt and is very difficult, success rates are really low. If you plan on hunting this unit, scouting is a must.

Behavior: As with most big game animals the early mornings and evenings are the best times to find elk. This is when most rutting activity will take place as well.
Most spike bulls are with cow and calf herds during the hunts. Keep this in mind as you plan your hunt. There is a lot of pressure put on these elk during the general season hunts, this will push the elk towards private land or areas with difficult access or terrain. After opening morning spend your time hunting the thick timber canyons or large aspen stands. Road hunting is not a very effective method of hunting during the general season.

Elk rut: There will typically be a little rutting activity starting the first part of September, with the peak of the rut being September 15th-the end of September. There will still be some rutting activity in October, but it will be winding down by then.

Recommended areas Anthro Unit from West to East:
Indian Canyon- can only hunt the East side of Highway 191, unless you have the January hunt. Not great during the early seasons, but can be a great place during the later seasons. Steep hillsides, and big canyons. Great place to glass.
Cottonwood Ridge- difficult access, better hunting on the late hunts, the best areas are the highest elevation.
Sowers Canyon- good access, many large canyons to glass. During the earlier hunts the far South end of the Canyon is best. The entire canyon is good during the late hunts.
Wire Fence Ridge- plenty of road access. Large aspen stands near the top of the ridge, there are also several steep hillsides that have been burned and these areas are great during late summer and early fall. Large sage brush flats, great area to hunt on the later hunts.
Nutters Ridge- Main road access for the Anthro Mountain portion of the unit. Very similar to Wire Fence, good aspen stands up high and several water troughs and springs. The far North end of this ridge is currently being drilled heavily for oil, avoid these areas.
Jeep Trail- good access, a few good aspen stands and burned areas. The far North end of this ridge also has had substantial drilling activity, with many new roads, elk will avoid these areas. There have been several habitat treatments done in this area.
Alkaline/Choke Cherry area- Really open area up high, several springs and guzzlers in this area as well. The open areas can hold many large herds of elk in the late fall and wintert. Lots of road access on small secondary ridges.
Gilsonite Area- Lower elevation area. Lots of pinyon/juniper and sage brush draws. There are several guzzlers in this area. Most of the elk will be near these water sources on the early hunts. In order to hunt this area scouting is a must. Good road access. This area is best when there is deep snow in the high elevation areas.

huntBoundaryInfos.LAND_OWNERSHIP: Public, Private and Tribal Lands.  The public lands are primarily US Forest Service lands managed by the Ashley National Forest and The Bureau of Land Management(BLM) managed out of the Vernal Field Office.  This unit also includes large tracks of Ute Tribal lands that are closed to non-tribal members. The Tribal lands are mostly on the North end of the unit in the pinyon/juniper belt, with heavy oil field activity. The private land on the unit is primarily North of the Tribal boundary and in the low elevation desert areas and agricultural lands. There is one CWMU on the unit (Antelope Creek).
huntBoundaryInfos.CAMPGRND_INFO:
There are no official campgrounds on this unit. except. Camping outside of official campgrounds is permitted on most of the Forest. Please direct all questions regarding campground availability and other camping questions to the US Forest Service. Maps and camping regulations are available on their websites.
Anthro: http://www.fs.usda.gov/ashley

huntBoundaryInfos.ATV_VEH_ACCESS:
Most roads and ATV trails on this unit are managed by the US Forest Service and BLM and are covered on their Travel Management Plans. Please direct all questions regarding which roads and trails ATVs can be operated on to the US Forest Service and BLM.
Anthro: http://www.fs.usda.gov/ashley
BLM: http://www.blm.gov/ut/st/en/fo/vernal.html
huntBoundaryInfos.PRIV_TRIBE_LAND_ISSUES: The Anthro unit contains large amounts of Tribal Trust Lands. All ATVs are prohibited on Tribal Lands and must be trailered on access roads across Tribal Lands.  For information on which roads are legal access roads contact Duchesne County. There are also several large areas of private land on the unit, including 1 large CWMU. Hunters must receive written permission before hunting private lands.
huntBoundaryInfos.BOUNDARY_DESCRIPTION: Duchesne and Uintah counties--Boundary begins at US-40 and US-191 at Duchesne; south on US-191 to Argyle Canyon Road; southeast on this road to Nine Mile Canyon Road; east on this road to Gate Canyon and the Nine Mile Canyon Backcountry Byway; north on this byway to the BLM boundary near Pleasant Valley; east on this boundary to the Green River near Pariette Draw; northeast along this river to the Duchesne River; northwest along this river to US-40 at Myton; west on US-40 to US-191. EXCLUDES ALL NATIVE AMERICAN TRUST LANDS WITHIN THIS BOUNDARY. Excludes all CWMUs. USGS 1:100,000 Maps: Duchesne, Price, Vernal.  Boundary Questions?  Call Vernal Office, 435-781-9453.
